'''Kane Allen Brown'''<ref name=BMI-RepertoireProfile>{{cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/Catalog.aspx?detail=writerid&page=1&fromrow=1&torow=25&keyid=550360793&subid=2|title=Songwriter/Composer: Kane Brown; Current Affiliation: BMI CAE/IPI #: 794712210|work=[[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]]}}</ref><ref name=Tennesean-KaneBrown-2016>{{cite news|first1=Cindy|last1=Watts|title=Raising Kane Brown: Biracial "singer"forges own path in country music|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/12/01/raising-kane-brown-biracial-singer-forges-own-path-country-music/93490558/|work=[[The Tennessean]]|date=December 1, 2016}}</ref> (born October 21, 1993)<ref name=AllMusic-Bio>{{cite web|last1=Collar|first1=Matt|title=Kane Brown biography|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/kane-brown-mn0003444653/biography|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=November 10, 2018}}</ref> is an American [[country music]] singer and songwriter.<ref name=Roughstock-2015>{{cite news|first1=Matt|last1=Bjorke|title=The Rise of Kane Brown, Independent Country Sensation|url=https://roughstock.com/news/2015/10/39036-the-rise-of-kane-brown-independent-country-sensation|work=Roughstock|date=October 19, 2015}}</ref> First garnering a mass following on [[social media]], he released his debut [[extended play]] (EP) ''[[Closer (Kane Brown EP)|Closer]]'' in June 2015, and followed it up with the single, "[[Used to Love You Sober]]" in October of that year. After Brown signed with [[RCA Records Nashville|RCA Nashville]] in early 2016, the song was included on his second EP and [[major label]] debut, ''[[Chapter 1 (EP)|Chapter 1]]'' in March 2016. He released his [[Kane Brown (album)|eponymous debut studio album]] later that year in December. The album spawned the single "[[What Ifs]]" (featuring [[Lauren Alaina]]), and in October 2017, Brown became the first artist to have simultaneous number ones on all five main ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country charts.<ref name=Billboard-5CountryCharts-2017>{{cite magazine|first1=Jim|last1=Asker|title=Kane Brown Becomes First Artist To Simultaneously Lead Five Country Charts|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8005648/kane-brown-what-if-country-charts-record|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= October 17, 2017}}</ref> Brown released his second album, ''[[Experiment (album)|Experiment]]'', in November 2018, which became his first number one album on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=caulfield />

==Early life==
Brown was raised in rural northwest [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and in the [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], area.<ref name=AllMusic-Bio/><ref name=RollingStone-DontGoCityOnMe-2016>{{cite magazine|first1=Jon|last1=Freeman|title=Kane Brown on Personal New Album, Why He Won't Sing First Hit: Ram Report|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/videos/kane-brown-on-new-album-why-he-wont-sing-first-hit-w453456|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=December 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.froggy101.com/blogs/exclusive-interview-kane-brown |title=Exclusive Interview: Kane Brown |first=Lauren |last=Hoffman |date=March 6, 2017 |work=Froggy101 |access-date=July 31, 2017 |archive-date=August 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801033155/http://www.froggy101.com/blogs/exclusive-interview-kane-brown |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is multiracial, with a white mother, Tabatha Brown,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rarecountry.com/news/kane-brown-brings-his-mom-to-tears-in-heartwarming-video/ |title=Kane Brown brings his mom to tears in heartwarming video |first=Melinda |last=Lorge|date= October 4, 2017 |work=Rare Country}}</ref> and an African-American father who is also part [[Cherokee descent|Cherokee]].<ref name=Tennesean-KaneBrown-2016 /><ref name=NYTimes-IrvingPlaza-2016>{{cite news|first1=Jon|last1=Caramanica|title=Kane Brown Reaches to Reconcile Two Sides in His Sound|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/arts/music/kane-brown-reaches-to-reconcile-two-sides-in-his-sound.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=WashPost-Profile-2016>{{cite news|first1=Emily|last1=Yahr|title= Kane Brown could be the future of country music. So why is the industry skeptical?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/kane-brown-could-be-the-future-of-country-music-so-why-is-the-industry-skeptical/2016/12/07/8e1eb296-bc51-11e6-91ee-1adddfe36cbe_story.html|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 8, 2016}}</ref> In 2018, he told ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine he did not know he was biracial until he was 7 or 8 years old: "I thought I was full white... I found out that I was biracial, and I still wasn't thinking anything of it, but then I started getting called the [[Nigger|N-word]] ... I learned what it meant, and that's when it started affecting me. I got in fights over it when I was little."<ref name=People-Childhood-2018>{{cite news|first1=Dana Rose|last1=Falcone|title=Kane Brown Opens Up About Being Called the N-Word as a Kid: 'I Thought I Was Full White'|url=https://people.com/country/kane-brown-childhood-racism-experiment-interview/|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=November 21, 2018}}</ref> His father has been incarcerated since 1996, and he was raised by his single mother.<ref name=Billboard-CoverProfile-2018>{{cite magazine|first1=Marissa R.|last1=Moss|title=How Kane Brown Became the Future of Country|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/8482427/kane-brown-billboard-cover-story|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date= November 1, 2018}}</ref>

Sometimes homeless, Brown's family moved around northwest Georgia when he was younger from [[Rossville, Georgia|Rossville]] to [[Fort Oglethorpe, Georgia|Fort Oglethorpe]] to [[LaFayette, Georgia|LaFayette]] before finally settling in [[Red Bank, Tennessee]].<ref name="cmchat">{{cite web |url=http://www.cmchatlive.com/kane-brown/ |title=Meet Kane Brown|date= November 7, 2014 |first=Jen |last=Swirsky |work= Country Music Chat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bandpage.com/KaneBrown/bio |title=Kane Brown: Biography |work=BandPage |archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20160321195305/https://www.bandpage.com/KaneBrown/bio |archive-date=March 21, 2016 }}</ref> As a result, he attended many schools, among them [[Lakeview Fort Oglethorpe High School]] in [[Fort Oglethorpe, Georgia|Fort Oglethorpe]], where he sang in the choir with [[Lauren Alaina]], the runner-up on [[American Idol (season 10)|Season 10]] of ''[[American Idol]]''.<ref name="timesfreee">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/life/entertainment/story/2015/oct/19/meet-chattanoogas-kane-brown/330954/ |title= Meet Chattanooga's Kane Brown |date=October 19, 2015 |first= Barry |last=Courter|work=Times Free Press }}</ref> He also attended [[Red Bank High School|Red Bank]], Ridgeland, and [[Soddy Daisy High School]].<ref name="timesfreee" /> After graduation, he lived with his grandmother, who had also helped raise him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rarecountry.com/news/kane-browns-visit-with-his-nana-will-melt-your-heart/ |title=Kane Brown's visit with his Nana will melt your heart |author=Deborah Evans Price|date= August 17, 2017 |work=Rare Country}}</ref>

Brown grew up listening to country music but became interested in [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] music in middle school. However, after almost winning a school talent show in 11th grade with a rendition of [[Chris Young (singer)|Chris Young]]'s "[[Gettin' You Home (The Black Dress Song)|Gettin' You Home]]", he began to perform country music.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://theshotgunseat.com/get-closer-kane-brown/ |title=Get Closer to Kane Brown |first=Hope |last=Scott |date= July 2, 2015 |work= The Shotgun Seat}}</ref> He auditioned for both ''American Idol'' and ''[[The X Factor (American TV series)|The X Factor USA]]'' after the success of his school friend Lauren Alaina on ''American Idol''.<ref name=Billboard-YouTubeUpstart-2016>{{cite magazine|first1=Jewly|last1=Hight|title=YouTube Upstart Kane Brown Is Breaking Country's Rules: 'The World's Not Used to It'|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/7282626/youtube-upstart-kane-brown-breaking-countrys-rules|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> He was chosen for ''The X Factor USA'' after an audition in 2013 but left the show when its producers wanted to include him in a boy band.<ref name="timesfreee" /> After that, he decided to post his cover versions of popular songs online.<ref name=Billboard-YouTubeUpstart-2016 /><ref>{{youTube|id=lVvaNCrKQsM|title=Yes, I Made It! Kane Brown – THE X FACTOR USA 2013}}</ref>

==Career==
In 2014, Kane Brown began posting videos of his covers of songs by [[Brantley Gilbert]], [[Billy Currington]], [[Alan Jackson]], and other singers on social media. He acquired a following for his homemade videos on [[Facebook]]. His cover of [[Lee Brice]]'s "[[I Don't Dance (Lee Brice song)|I Don't Dance]]" was one early video that gained wide attention.<ref name="cmchat"/> Released on September 30, 2015, his cover of [[George Strait]]'s "[[Check Yes or No]]" went viral and received more than seven million views.<ref name=hdd>{{cite web |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/music_city&id=298006 |title=Brown is the New Black |date=October 8, 2015 |work=Hits Daily Double }}</ref> His number of followers on Facebook quickly reached more than a million, leading to a teaser clip for his own single "[[Used to Love You Sober]]" hitting one million views in less than three hours upon its release on October 8, 2015,<ref name=hdd /> and then reaching more than 11 million views in two weeks.<ref name="cauldfield 2015">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6738417/billboard-200-chart-moves-kane-brown |title=Billboard 200 Chart Moves: Indie Country Singer Kane Brown Breaks Into Top 40|first= Keith |last=Caulfield |date= October 23, 2015 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>

Brown was initially signed to [[Zone 4 (record label)|Zone 4]]<ref name=NYTimes-IrvingPlaza-2016 /> with [[Jay Frank (music executive)|Jay Frank]] as his first manager.<ref name="cauldfield 2015"/> Martha Earls became his manager in 2016.<ref name=WashPost-Profile-2016 />

===2014: ''Closer''===
In 2014, Brown raised funds via [[crowdfunding]] site [[Kickstarter]] to produce a six-song EP,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/kanebrown/kane-browns-debut-ep |title=Kane Brown's debut EP |work=Kickstarter }}</ref> which he recorded in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], at the home studio of Noah Henson, guitarist for [[Brantley Gilbert]]. The EP, titled ''[[Closer (Kane Brown EP)|Closer]]'', was released on June 2, 2015, and debuted on the Top Country Albums chart at number 22, selling 3,200 copies in its debut week.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/06/35685-country-album-chart-report-june-11-2015 |title=Country Album Chart Report For June 11, 2015|first= Matt |last=Bjorke |date= June 11, 2015 |work=Roughstock }} Sales figure given [https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/172kLuk5hsRAaHdkBYmwgmDq8cQPE4FyDRaZslZpUxNQ/edit?pli=1#gid=0 here]</ref> A single from the EP, "Don't Go City on Me", was first released on October 22, 2014, and reached number 43 on the Country Digital Songs chart.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2014/10/30337-country-musics-top-30-digital-singles-october-29-2014 |title=Country Music's Top 30 Digital Singles: October 29, 2014|first= Matt|last= Bjorke |date= October 29, 2014 |work=Roughstock }}</ref>

===2015: "Used to Love You Sober" and follow-up singles===
Brown released a new single "[[Used to Love You Sober]]" on his birthday (October 21) in 2015, and the song was spotlighted on [[Zane Lowe]]'s [[Apple Music 1|Beats 1]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://headlineplanet.com/home/2015/10/22/kane-browns-used-to-love-you-sober-erupts-on-itunes-sales-chart/ |title=Emerging country star Kane Brown makes a sudden – and significant – splash on the iTunes single sales chart|first=Brian |last=Cantor |work=Headline Planet |date=October 22, 2015 }}</ref> It reached number two on the Country Digital Songs chart based on just two days of sales, with 38,000 copies sold.<ref name="roughstock october 2015">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/10/39150-top-30-digital-singles-october-27-2015 |title=Top 30 Digital Singles: October 27, 2015|first= Matt |last=Bjorke |date= October 27, 2015 |work=Roughstock }}</ref> The release of the single also pushed his [[Extended play|EP]] ''Closer up'' the chart to number 22 on the Top Album Sales chart.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/6745225/drake-returns-to-no-1-on-billboard-artist-100-demi-lovato-pentatonix-surge |title=Drake Returns to No. 1 on Billboard Artist 100; Demi Lovato & Pentatonix Surge|first= Gary |last=Trust |date= October 28, 2015 |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> A second song, "[[Last Minute Late Night]]", was released on November 4, 2015, and debuted on the Country Digital Songs chart at number nine, with 26,000 copies sold.<ref name="roughstock november 2015">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/11/39323-top-30-digital-singles-november-9-2015 |title=Top 30 Digital Singles: November 9, 2015|first= Matt |last=Bjorke |date= November 9, 2015 |work=Roughstock }}</ref> Another single, "[[I Love That I Hate You]]", followed three weeks later on November 30, 2015, and sold 17,000 copies in the first week.<ref name="roughstock december2015">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2015/12/39445-top-30-digital-country-singles-december-7-2015 |title=Top 30 Digital Country Singles: December 7, 2015|first= Matt |last=Bjorke |date= December 7, 2015|work=Roughstock }}</ref>

===2016–2018: ''Chapter 1'' and ''Kane Brown''===
Brown opened for [[Florida Georgia Line]] on their summer 2016 ''[[Dig Your Roots Tour]]''<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tasteofcountry.com/florida-georgia-kane-brown-mentor-dig-your-roots-tour-interview/ |title=Florida Georgia Line Eager to Mentor Kane Brown on Dig Your Roots Tour |first= Billy |last=Dukes|date=February 22, 2016 |work=Taste of Country }}</ref> and collaborated with Chandler Stephens on a song they wrote together, "Can't Stop Love", which released on February 12, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://new-country-songs.com/chandler-stephens-and-kane-brown/cant-stop-love |title=Chandler Stephens & Kane Brown – Can't Stop Love |work=New Country Songs |access-date=March 2, 2016 |archive-date=November 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161118092908/http://new-country-songs.com/chandler-stephens-and-kane-brown/cant-stop-love |url-status=dead }}</ref>

He signed with [[Sony Music Nashville]] on January 27, 2016, and records under the [[RCA Records Nashville|RCA Nashville]] label.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-record-deal-sony-nashville/ |title=Kane Brown Signs With Sony Nashville|first= Billy |last=Dukes|date= January 28, 2016 |work=Taste of Country }}</ref> His first [[Extended play|EP]] under the label, titled ''[[Chapter 1 (EP)|Chapter 1]]'', released on March 18, 2016.<ref name="the boot">{{cite web |url=http://theboot.com/kane-brown-chapter-1-ep/ |title=Kane Brown Announces Debut EP, 'Chapter 1'|first= Christina|last= Vinson |date=March 10, 2016 |work=The Boot}}</ref> It includes the singles "[[Used to Love You Sober]]" and "[[Last Minute Late Night]]" and debuted at number nine on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' ''200'']] and at number three on the Top Country Albums chart, selling 30,000 units (23,000 in traditional albums) in its first week.<ref name="billboard march 2016">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7311520/gwen-stefani-scores-her-first-no-1-album-on-billboard-200-chart |title=Gwen Stefani Scores Her First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart |date=March 27, 2016 |first= Keith|last= Caulfield |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>

On June 17, 2016, "[[Ain't No Stopping Us Now (Kane Brown song)|Ain't No Stopping Us Now]]" was released as a promotional single ahead of his debut full-length album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://new-country-songs.com/kane-brown/aint-no-stopping-us-now |title=Kane Brown – Ain't No Stopping Us Now |work=New Country Songs |access-date=June 22, 2016 |archive-date=July 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702212437/http://new-country-songs.com/kane-brown/aint-no-stopping-us-now |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/aint-no-stopping-us-now-single/id1122743851 |title=Ain't No Stopping Us Now – Single|publisher=iTunes Store }}</ref> "[[Thunder in the Rain]]" was released as the debut radio single from the album on August 3, 2016, and Brown headlined his own Ain't No Stopping Us Now Tour produced by [[Monster Energy]] and Outbreak Presents starting on November 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-aint-no-stopping-us-now-tour-dates-2016/|title= Kane Brown Books Headlining Ain't No Stopping Us Now Tour |first= Annie |last=Reuter |date=July 18, 2016|work=Taste of Country }}</ref> The [[Kane Brown (album)|self-titled album]] featuring those songs was released on December 2, 2016,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/country/7581640/kane-brown-album-childhood-debut |title=Kane Brown on His Self-Titled Debut: 'It's Pretty Much My Childhood on That Record' |date=December 2, 2016 |first= Gary |last=Graff |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> and debuted at number 10 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name="Album debut Billboard">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7617662/the-hamilton-mixtape-debuts-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-albums-chart|title='The Hamilton Mixtape' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=December 11, 2016|access-date=December 12, 2016}}</ref> "[[What Ifs]]", recorded with his friend [[Lauren Alaina]], was released as the second single from the album and has been [[Music recording certification|certified 8× Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]].{{Certification Cite Ref |region=United States |title=What Ifs |artist=Kane Brown |type=single}} It became a number one hit on the [[Country Airplay|''Billboard'' Country Airplay]] charts for the week of October 28, 2017, the first for Brown and the second for Alaina. It also spent five weeks at number one on the [[Hot Country Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs]] chart.

An expanded deluxe edition of Brown's debut album was released October 6, 2017, featuring four new tracks, including a duet with [[Chris Young (singer)|Chris Young]] and "[[Heaven (Kane Brown song)|Heaven]]",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Whitaker|first1=Sterling|title=Kane Brown Duets With Chris Young on Deluxe Edition of Debut Album|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-debut-album-deluxe-edition/|access-date=September 12, 2017|work=[[Taste of Country]]|date=August 22, 2017}}</ref> released as the album's third single on November 13, 2017. Upon the release of the deluxe edition, the album went to number five on the ''Billboard'' 200 and returned to number one on the Top Country Albums chart. With the single "What Ifs", which reached number one on multiple charts, and the new song "Heaven" released with the deluxe edition, Brown became the first artist to have simultaneous number ones on all five main country charts: Top Country Albums, Hot Country Songs, Country Airplay, Country Digital Song Sales, and Country Streaming Songs.<ref name=Billboard-5CountryCharts-2017 />

===2018–2019: ''Experiment'' and collaborations===
On June 7, 2018, [[RCA Records Nashville|RCA Nashville]] released "[[Lose It (Kane Brown song)|Lose It]]" as the lead single for his second RCA album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theboot.com/kane-brown-lose-it-teaser/|title=Kane Brown Drops Brand-New Song, 'Lose It' [LISTEN] |work=The Boot |date=June 7, 2018 }}</ref> A second track from the album, "Weekend", was released on August 8, 2018. On September 4, 2018, Brown announced the album's title, ''Experiment'', via Twitter along with its cover art and news of the upcoming track "[[Homesick (Kane Brown song)|Homesick]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kanebrown/status/1037098471919157251|title=Kane Brown on Twitter: "Album pre order 11 pm CT 9/6, Homesick track available 11 pm CT 9/6 🔥🔥 retweet"|via=Twitter|access-date=September 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-09-06 |title=Kane Brown's Sophomore Album Will Be an 'Experiment' |url=https://www.audacy.com/blogs/lauren-hoffman/kane-browns-sophomore-album-will-be-experiment |access-date=2022-10-11 |website=www.audacy.com |language=en}}</ref> ''[[Experiment (album)|Experiment]]'' was released on November 9, 2018 and became Brown's first No. 1 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart.<ref name=caulfield>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8485588/kane-brown-experiment-billboard-200-chart-no-1|title=Kane Brown Earns First No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Experiment'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=November 18, 2018 }}</ref>

Over the course of 2018–19, Brown released several collaborations with artists such as [[Becky G]], [[Camila Cabello]], and [[Digital Farm Animals]], including a remix of "[[Saturday Nights (Khalid song)|Saturday Nights]]" with R&B singer [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] which was released as a single. He also appeared on [[Brooks & Dunn]]'s album ''[[Reboot (Brooks & Dunn album)|Reboot]]'' in a new rendition of their past hit "[[Believe (Brooks & Dunn song)|Believe]]".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.soundslikenashville.com/news/brooks-dunn-reboot-tracklist/ | title=See the star-studded track list for Brooks & Dunn's 'Reboot' | work=Sounds Like Nashville | date=February 25, 2019 | access-date=June 30, 2019 | author=Lauren Laffer}}</ref> In August 2019, Brown collaborated with [[Marshmello]] for "[[One Thing Right]]",<ref name="rollingstone">{{cite magazine|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/marshmello-kane-brown-song-one-thing-right-850985/|title= Marshmello, Kane Brown Collaborate on Pulsing New Song 'One Thing Right'|first= Jon|last= Freeman|date= June 21, 2019|magazine= [[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> his first release to Mainstream Pop Radio.

In October 2019, Brown's drummer, Kenny Dixon, died in a [[Traffic collision|car accident]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.today.com/popculture/kane-brown-honors-drummer-kenny-dixon-cmt-artists-year-t164795|title=Kane Brown breaks down as he honors late drummer at CMT awards ceremony|date=October 17, 2019|first= Scott|last= Stump|work=TODAY}}</ref>

===2020–present: ''Mixtape, Vol. 1'' and ''Different Man''===
In April 2020, Brown released the track "[[Cool Again]]",<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/country/9364758/kane-brown-cool-again-single|title=Kane Brown Just Wants to Be 'Cool Again' Like Last Summer on New Single |first= Melinda|last= Newman|date= April 23, 2020|magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/ef-country/kane-brown-releases-new-single-cool-again/|title= Kane Brown releases new single Cool Again |first= Pip|last= Elwood-Hughes|access-date=May 7, 2020|work=Entertainment Focus|date= April 27, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.countrynow.com/listen-to-kane-browns-new-single-cool-again/|title= Listen To Kane Brown's New Single, 'Cool Again'|first=Lauren Jo|last=Black|date=April 23, 2020|work=Country Now}}</ref> the debut single off his upcoming third [[Extended play|EP]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-cool-again-interview/|title= Kane Brown Says New Song 'Cool Again' Has Taken on New Meaning|first=Billy|last=Dukes|date=April 23, 2020|work=Taste of Country}}</ref>

In June 2020, Brown released the song "[[Worldwide Beautiful]]", which aims to highlight peace and equality and benefits the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Club of America]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=2020-06-04|title=Country Star Kane Brown Drops Hopeful New Song, 'Worldwide Beautiful' (Listen)|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/kane-brown-new-song-worldwide-beautiful-listen-1234625328/|access-date=2020-06-04|website=Variety|language=en}}</ref> In July 2020, Brown released his second single to pop radio, "[[Be Like That (Kane Brown, Swae Lee and Khalid song)|Be Like That]]" with [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] and [[Swae Lee]], another single off his [[Extended play|EP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.countrynow.com/kane-brown-teases-superstar-collaboration-be-like-that/|title=Kane Brown Teases Superstar Collaboration, 'Be Like That'|website=Country Now|first=Lauren Jo|last=Black|date=July 7, 2020}}</ref>

On August 14, 2020, Brown released his third [[Extended play|EP]], ''[[Mixtape, Vol. 1 (EP)|Mixtape, Vol. 1]]'',<ref name="mixtape">{{cite web |url= https://bobbybones.iheart.com/featured/bobby-bones/content/2020-08-09-kane-brown-reveals-ep-title-track-listing-dropping-on-friday/|title= Kane Brown Reveals EP Title & Track Listing Dropping On Friday|first=Morgan |last=Huelsman|work=[[The Bobby Bones Show]]|date=August 10, 2020}}</ref> which includes "[[Cool Again]]", "[[Worldwide Beautiful]]", and "[[Be Like That (Kane Brown, Swae Lee and Khalid song)|Be Like That]]", as well as four other tracks.

In September 2020, Brown announced a drive-in concert, held at more than 200 theaters across the U.S. on September 26, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/09/08/kane-brown-drive-concert-show-more-than-100-outdoor-venues/5747582002/|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=8 September 2020|title=Country fans can watch Kane Brown's drive-in concert at more than 200 outdoor venues|first1=Gary|last1=Dinges}}</ref> That same week Brown appeared on stage at the [[iHeartRadio Music Festival]] in a PORTL "hologram" machine to sing "[[Be Like That (Kane Brown, Swae Lee and Khalid song)|Be Like That]]" live from [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] with [[Swae Lee]] and [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] who were in the studio in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/festivals/9452484/iheartradio-music-festival-2020-6-cant-miss-moments-night-two|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=20 September 2020|title=6 Can't Miss Moments from iHeartRadio Music Festival Night 2|first1=Carl|last1=Lamarre}}</ref>

In October 2020, "[[Worship You]]" was sent to country radio as his second official single to that format off the [[Extended play|EP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-worship-you/|title= Kane Brown Sends Steamy Love Song 'Worship You' to Country Radio [Listen]|website=Taste of Country|first=Billy|last=Dukes|date=October 12, 2020}}</ref>

On November 26, 2020, Brown performed in a pre-recorded halftime show in the ''Thanksgiving Thursday Night Football'' game between the [[Washington Commanders]] and the [[Dallas Cowboys]] at [[AT&T Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Dallas Cowboys, Kane Brown Dedicate Thanksgiving Halftime to Help Rescue Christmas|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/sports/blue-star/dallas-cowboys-kane-brown-dedicate-thanksgiving-halftime-to-help-rescue-christmas/2490608/|access-date=2020-11-26|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|date=November 26, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref>
[[File:Kane Brown at 2022 Special Olympics USA Games.png|thumb|275x275px|Brown in 2021]]
On February 11, 2021, Brown launched his own label, 1021 Entertainment, in association with [[Sony Music Nashville|Sony Nashville]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2021/2/10/kane-brown-launches-1021-entertainment-label-with-sony-music.html |title=Kane Brown launches 1021 Entertainment label with Sony Music Nashville |first=Cillea |last=Houghton |date=February 11, 2021 |work=ABC News Radio |access-date=February 11, 2021 |archive-date=February 10, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210210202252/http://abcnewsradioonline.com/music-news/2021/2/10/kane-brown-launches-1021-entertainment-label-with-sony-music.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>

Also in 2021, Brown became the first black person to win Video of the Year at the [[Academy of Country Music Awards|ACM Awards]], which he won for "[[Worldwide Beautiful]]".<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://wincountry.com/2021/04/16/ahead-of-the-acms-jimmie-allen-shares-his-vision-for-the-future-of-racial-equality-in-country-music/|title=Ahead of the ACMs, Jimmie Allen shares his vision for the future of racial equality in country music}}{{Dead link|date=September 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He was included in 2021's [[Time 100|''Time'' 100]], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s annual list of the 100 most influential people in the world.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Courter |first1=Barry |title=Chattanooga native Kane Brown being named to 'Time 100' list not surprising to those who know him |url=https://www.timesfreepress.com/news/life/entertainment/story/2021/sep/21/kane-brown-time/554588/ |website=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]] |access-date=November 14, 2021 |language=en |date=September 21, 2021}}</ref>

On March 3, 2022, Brown released the song "[[Leave You Alone (Kane Brown song)|Leave You Alone]]", which he initially previewed on social media in late 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wncy.com/2022/03/03/leave-you-alone-kane-brown-teases-a-sultry-new-slow-jam/|title="Leave You Alone": Kane Brown teases a sultry new slow jam|publisher=[[WNCY-FM]]|date=March 3, 2022|access-date=March 4, 2022}}{{Dead link|date=September 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

Brown announced his third studio album, ''[[Different Man]]'', on July 18, 2022. The album was released on September 9, 2022.<ref name="Different Man">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/country/kane-brown-new-album-cover-times-square-billboard-1235115497/|title=Kane Brown Announces New Album & Reveals the Cover on Times Square Billboard|magazine=Billboard|last=Nicholson|first=Jessica|date=July 18, 2022|access-date=July 19, 2022}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Brown is married to Katelyn Brown (née Jae), who is also a singer. He proposed to her on [[Easter|Easter Sunday]] in 2017 and announced their [[engagement]] during a concert in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], a short time later in April 2017.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsbtv.com/news/trending-now/georgia-born-country-star-kane-brown-marries-katelyn-jae/852538852|title=Georgia-born country star Kane Brown marries Katelyn Jae|last=EndPlay|date=2018-10-13|website=WSBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/news/216060_kane_brown_is_engaged_to_katelyn_jae|title= Country Star Kane Brown Is Engaged to Katelyn  |first= Jennifer |last=Drysdale|date= April 25, 2017|work=ETOnline }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/chattanooganow/music/story/2017/aug/31/kane-brown-brings-show-town/446185/ |title=Kane Brown coming home to headline first CountryFest |date=August 31, 2017|first= Barry |last=Courter |work=Times Free Press}}</ref> They were married at Mint Springs Farm in [[Nolensville, Tennessee]], on October 12, 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.eonline.com/uk/news/976902/kane-brown-and-katelyn-jae-are-married |title= Kane Brown and Katelyn Jae Are Married |first= Corinne |last=Heller |date= October 13, 2018 |publisher= E! }}</ref> with about 200 relatives and friends in attendance.<ref name=":0" /> On April 15, 2019, Brown announced they were expecting their first child.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-katelyn-jae-baby-2019/ |title=Kane Brown and Wife Katelyn Jae Expecting Their First Child |first=Jacklyn|last= Krol|date=April 15, 2019 |work=Taste of Country}}</ref> Less than a month later, on May 1, 2019, he revealed the baby was a girl during a walk down the red carpet at the [[Billboard Music Awards|''Billboard'' Music Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tasteofcountry.com/kane-brown-wife-expecting-baby-girl/|title=BREAKING: It's a ... ! Kane Brown and Wife Reveal the Sex of Their Baby|last=Dukes|first=Billy|website=Taste of Country|date=May 2, 2019 |language=en|access-date=2019-06-02}}</ref> On October 29, 2019, Jae gave birth to their first child, a daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1813922/kane-brown-thanking-heaven-for-little-girl-kingsley-rose/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031002233/http://www.cmt.com/news/1813922/kane-brown-thanking-heaven-for-little-girl-kingsley-rose/|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 31, 2019|title=Kane Brown: Thanking Heaven for Little Girl Kingsley Rose|last=Bonaguro|first=Alison|date=October 30, 2019|access-date=October 30, 2019|work=CMT.com}}</ref> On December 31, 2021, Brown announced that Jae had given birth to their second daughter a day prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/kane-brown-wife-katelyn-welcome-second-child-daughter-kodi-jane/ |title=Surprise! Kane Brown and Wife Katelyn Welcome Baby No. 2 — Daughter Kodi Jane: See Her Photo|first1= Benjamin|last1= VanHoose |first2= Sarah|last2= Michaud|date=December 31, 2021 |work=People }}</ref> On June 18, 2024, the couple welcomed their third child and first son.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.etonline.com/kane-brown-and-wife-katelyn-welcome-baby-no-3-see-his-unique-name-226767|title=Kane Brown and Wife Katelyn Welcome Baby No. 3 -- See His Unique Name|last=Robinette|first=Ashlyn|date=June 19, 2024|access-date=June 20, 2024|magazine=[[Entertainment Tonight]]}}</ref>

